The park has a nice diversity of habitats and would be a great place to spend an entire day walking -- many trails.----Trolled unsuccessfully at several spots for WEWA, and at one spot for BHNU----<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/35021553952/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto SP""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4220/35021553952_84bda51389_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto SP"" /></a>--<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/35021563482/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto SP""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4213/35021563482_b6a1862c9a_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto SP"" /></a>--<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/35056063201/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto SP""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4285/35056063201_d820dc7775_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto SP"" /></a>--<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/35146506926/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto SP""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4273/35146506926_3b80b0b840_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto SP"" /></a>--<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/35186762855/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto SP""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4265/35186762855_65c68a9726_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto SP"" /></a>--<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/34342040964/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto River""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4207/34342040964_73957d76fe_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto River"" /></a>--<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/34800203980/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto SP""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4256/34800203980_3e6d34742a_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto SP"" /></a>--<a href=""https://www.flickr.com/photos/126193733@N06/35186869315/in/datetaken-public/"" title=""Bogue Chitto SP""><img src=""https://c1.staticflickr.com/5/4249/35186869315_6d452b74c2_b.jpg"" alt=""Bogue Chitto SP"" /></a>"

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS581124419	2018-08-06 18:44:04	27249	species	Wood Thrush	Hylocichla mustelina			4				United States	US	Louisiana	US-LA	West Feliciana	US-LA-125		27			West Fork Thompson's Creek	L6973813	P	30.9541315	-91.3081026	1988-06-16	08:00:00	obsr125749	S43103847	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	390	6.437		2	1		0	1	0		"With David Pashley, surveying for Worm-eating Warblers and Louisiana Waterthrushes.  Hiked down river, leaving cars at two bridges (one 4 miles east of Wakefield, the other upriver near Coerner).  Hot, mostly clear day (to about 90 F).  Floodplain 100 feet wide, wide sand and fine gravel, flat; creek 10-40 ft wide, ankle deep mostly (never knee deep).  We walked in tennis shoes, crossing creek often; some ""quicksand"", sinking up to knees;not a hard-packed surface, which made walking tiring.  Woods intact on either side of creek; appears extensive in lower half.  River trees mainly sycamore, river bird, water oak, Carpinus, box elder; some sweet gum, willow, wax myrtle, beech, magnolia, swamp chestnut oak; no cypress.  Birds sang fairly well in AM, except our targets, Worm-eating and Waterthrush (chipping, mainly).  The Screech-owl tape was essential for seeing many birds.  We played it 13 times at sites 100-150 meters or more apart."
